abstract = {In the past years the conservation of forest genetic resources has been$\backslash$nwidely recognized because of the risk of adverse effects associated with$\backslash$nglobal changes in the environment. Since little effort has been made$\backslash$ntowards conservation of these resources, the assessment and the$\backslash$nintegration of information and knowledge so far generated are valuable$\backslash$ntools in order to promote their conservation. In the present work the$\backslash$nBrazilian conifer Araucaria angustifolia was used as a case study,$\backslash$nintegrating information, published between 1980 and 2007, about$\backslash$ngenetics, biotechnology, palaeobotany, and archeology. These studies$\backslash$nwere interpreted towards the conservation needs and strategies of the$\backslash$nspecies germplasm. The main conclusions for the conservation of A.$\backslash$nangustifolia genetic resources are: (1) despite the reduction of genetic$\backslash$ndiversity by unsustainable forest exploitation, the genetic system of A.$\backslash$nangustifolia seems to be efficient to protect this species against rapid$\backslash$nlosses of its genetic diversity; (2) conservation measures starting now$\backslash$nmay be efficient, since the genetic structures of existing populations$\backslash$nis more largely influenced by the past evolutionary process than by$\backslash$nhuman disturbance occurred in the last century; (3) there are$\backslash$nopportunities to save the genetic resources of the species, if simple$\backslash$nmeasures are taken to safeguard the continued existence of the few$\backslash$nremaining araucaria forests. Emerged as a general conclusion that the$\backslash$nuse of sound scientific arguments supported by different areas of the$\backslash$nscience could be a very powerful instrument in persuading$\backslash$ndecision-makers, also by governments, taking into account forest genetic$\backslash$nresources as a primary issue for the future.},
