@article{Pacala1996a,
abstract = {A spatial and mechanistic model is developed for the dynamics of transition$\backslash$noak-northern hardwoods forests in northeastern North America. The$\backslash$npurpose of the model is to extrapolate from measurable fine-scale$\backslash$nand short-term interactions among individual trees to large-scale$\backslash$nand long-term dynamics of forest communities. Field methods, statistical$\backslash$nestimators, and model structure were designed simultaneously to ensure$\backslash$nthat parameters could be estimated from data collected in the field.$\backslash$nThis paper documents eight aspects of a three-year study to calibrate,$\backslash$ntest, and analyze the model for the nine dominant and subdominant$\backslash$ntree species in transition oak-northern hardwoods forests: 1) Design$\backslash$nand structure of the model. The model makes population dynamic forecasts$\backslash$nby predicting the fate of every individual tree throughout its life.$\backslash$nSpecies-specific functions predict each tree's dispersal, establishment,$\backslash$ngrowth, mortality, and fecundity. Trees occupy unique spatial positions,$\backslash$nand individual performance is affected by the local availability$\backslash$nof resources. Competition is mechanistic; resources available to$\backslash$neach tree are reduced by neighbors. Although the model was developed$\backslash$nto include light, water, and nitrogen, the version described here$\backslash$nincludes only competition for light (shading and light-dependent$\backslash$nperformance) because the field data provide little evidence of competition$\backslash$nfor nitrogen and water over the range of sites examined. 2) Estimates$\backslash$nof the model's parameters for each species. The estimates reveal$\backslash$na variety of "strategic trade-offs" among the species. For example,$\backslash$nspecies that grow quickly under high light tend to cast relatively$\backslash$nlittle shade, have low survivorship under low light, and have high$\backslash$ndispersal. In contrast, species that grow slowly under high light$\backslash$ntend to cast relatively dark shade, and to have high survivorship$\backslash$nunder low light and low dispersal. These trade-offs define one of$\backslash$ntwo dominant "axes" of strategic variation. 3) Community level predictions$\backslash$nof the model. The model predicts succession from early dominance$\backslash$nby species such as Quercus rubra and Prunus serotina, to late dominance$\backslash$nby Fagus grandifolia and Tsuga canadensis, with Betula alleganiensis$\backslash$npresent as a gap phase species in old-growth stands. The model also$\backslash$npredicts that old-growth communities will have intraspecifically$\backslash$nclumped and interspecifically segregated spatial distributions. 4)$\backslash$nAn error analysis that identifies community level predictions that$\backslash$nare robust given the level of sampling uncertainty in the study.$\backslash$nThis analysis translates the statistical uncertainty associated with$\backslash$neach parameter estimate into statistical uncertainty in the model's$\backslash$npredictions. The robust predictions include those mentioned in aspect$\backslash$n(3) above. 5) Sensitivity of the model to changes in initial conditions$\backslash$nand to changes in the three parameters not included in the error$\backslash$nanalysis. For example, the model predicts that initial abundances$\backslash$ncontinue to affect community composition well into succession ({\textgreater}$\backslash$n300 yr for some species). 6) Tests of the system- and community-level$\backslash$npredictions of the model against independent data gleaned from other$\backslash$nstudies. These tests support the predictions found to be robust in$\backslash$nthe error analysis, including those predictions mentioned in aspect$\backslash$n(3) above. 7) Modeling experiments that determine which aspects of$\backslash$nindividual performance and inter-neighbor competition are responsible$\backslash$nfor each of the robust predictions identified in aspect (4) above$\backslash$nand tested in aspect (6) above. This analysis reveals a wide variety$\backslash$nof causal relationships, with most parameters contributing to at$\backslash$nleast one community level phenomenon. 8) An explanation of the diversity$\backslash$nof individual level causes identified in aspect (7). The two "axes"$\backslash$ndescribing most of the strategic variation among the species (see$\backslash$n[2]), provide a simple explanation of community level pattern in$\backslash$nterms of individual level processes.},
